answers.body_markdown:
The problem is you&#39;re not checking for any errors!

Always use `-&gt;error` in conjunction to any queries that you execute.

You can even add it simply on the same line:

    $result = mysqli_query($this-&gt;conn, $sql) or die($this-&gt;conn-&gt;error);
                                            //  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

The problematic line is the actual query:

    $sql = &quot;SELECT &quot; . $this-&gt;select . &quot; FROM &quot; . &quot;&#39;&quot; . $this-&gt;table . &quot;&#39;&quot;;
                                                // ^                    ^
If you want your table or column name to have quotes, use **backticks** &lt;code&gt;`&lt;/code&gt;. Thus the error false return value.

Once you&#39;ve fixed that, after executing the query, return the rows by `fetching`.

In this case you can use `-&gt;fetch_all()`.

So to stitch everything up:

    public function getAll()
    {
        $data = [];
        $sql = &quot;SELECT {$this-&gt;select} FROM {$this-&gt;table}&quot;;
        $result = mysqli_query($this-&gt;conn, $sql) or die($this-&gt;conn-&gt;error);
        $data = $result-&gt;fetch_all(MYSQLI_ASSOC);
        
        return $data; 
    }

Sidenote: You need to be careful though, anything can happen in your query if you don&#39;t whitelist your table and column names.

Another Note: To handle errors on your query since you&#39;re on development mode, set  the error reporting after you instantiate the connection object:

    public function connect()
    {
            $this-&gt;servername = &quot;localhost&quot;;
            $this-&gt;username = &quot;root&quot;;
            $this-&gt;password = &quot;&quot;;
            $this-&gt;dbname = &quot;test&quot;;
            $this-&gt;conn = new mysqli($this-&gt;servername, $this-&gt;username, $this-&gt;password, $this-&gt;dbname);
            // add this
            mysqli_report(MYSQLI_REPORT_ERROR | MYSQLI_REPORT_STRICT);
    
            return $this-&gt;conn;
        }
    }

So in turn you can use try and catch on your query execution. Then you&#39;ll know why your query failed.

    public function getAll()
    {
        $data = [];
        $sql = &quot;SELECT {$this-&gt;select} FROM {$this-&gt;table}&quot;;
        try {
            $result = mysqli_query($this-&gt;conn, $sql);
            $data = $result-&gt;fetch_all(MYSQLI_ASSOC);
        } catch (Exception $e) {
            echo &quot;SQL: [{$sql}] &quot; . $e-&gt;getMessage();
        }
    
        return $data; 
    }

